msgstr ""

#: cards:1
msgid ""
"<p>&nbsp;</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>&nbsp;</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>&nbsp;</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>The following guidelines are based on the National Council of Archives <em>Rules for the Construction of Personal, Place and Corporate Names.&nbsp;</em></p>\n"
"\n"
"<p><strong>Full Name</strong></p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>Use to record a concatenated form of the name. This can be useful for display or migration purposes but should not be used as a repalcement for the structured name data.</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p><strong>Title</strong></p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>In English only the titles Lord, Lady, Sir, Dame and Hon (Honourable) may precede the forename. However common practice allows for other titles, such as Mr, Mrs etc, to be used. Select the most appropriate.</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p><strong>Forename</strong></p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>A forename is the component of the name which a person is given in addition to his/her surname. All forenames, including middle names where known,&nbsp;should be listed to assist disambiguation between individuals.</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p><strong>Initials</strong></p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>These should only be used where the full name is not known&nbsp;or the individual is more usually known by their initials, eg. T.S. Eliot.&nbsp;</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p><strong>Surname</strong></p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>The component of a name which a person usually shares with other members of their family<strong>.</strong></p>\n"
"\n"
"<p><strong>Epithet</strong></p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>This is a word or phrase describing a person&#39;s status, position, occupation, nationality, place of birth etc. An epithet should be included as a qualifier where any confusion between persons may arise.</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>&nbsp;</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>&nbsp;</p>"
msgstr ""

#: cards:1
msgid ""
"<p><em>Archaeological Periods</em></p>\n"
"\n"
"<ul>\n"
"\t<li>Palaeolithic &nbsp;-1,000 000 to&nbsp;-10,000&nbsp;(BC)\n"
"\t<ul>\n"
"\t\t<li>Lower Palaeolithic &nbsp;-1,000 000 to&nbsp;-150,000</li>\n"
"\t\t<li>Middle Palaeolithic -150,000 to&nbsp;-40,000</li>\n"
"\t\t<li>Upper Palaeolithic -40,000 to&nbsp;-10,000</li>\n"
"\t</ul>\n"
"\t</li>\n"
"\t<li>Mesolithic -10,000 to&nbsp;-4,000\n"
"\t<ul>\n"
"\t\t<li>Early Mesolithic -10,000 to&nbsp; -7,000</li>\n"
"\t\t<li>Late Mesolithic -7,000 to&nbsp;-4,000</li>\n"
"\t</ul>\n"
"\t</li>\n"
"\t<li>Early Prehistoric -1,000 000 to&nbsp;-4,000</li>\n"
"\t<li>Neolithic -4,000 to&nbsp;-2,200\n"
"\t<ul>\n"
"\t\t<li>Early Neolithic -4,000 to&nbsp;-3,300</li>\n"
"\t\t<li>Middle Neolithic -3,300 to&nbsp;-2,900</li>\n"
"\t\t<li>Late Neolithic -2,900 to&nbsp;-2,200</li>\n"
"\t</ul>\n"
"\t</li>\n"
"\t<li>Bronze Age -2,600 to&nbsp;-700\n"
"\t<ul>\n"
"\t\t<li>Early Bronze Age -2,600 to&nbsp;-1,600</li>\n"
"\t\t<li>Middle Bronze Age -1,600 to&nbsp;-1,200</li>\n"
"\t\t<li>Late Bronze Age -1,200 to&nbsp;-700</li>\n"
"\t</ul>\n"
"\t</li>\n"
"\t<li>Iron Age -800 (BC) to 43 (AD)\n"
"\t<ul>\n"
"\t\t<li>Early Iron Age-800 to -300</li>\n"
"\t\t<li>Middle Iron Age -300 to&nbsp;-100</li>\n"
"\t\t<li>Late Iron Age -100 to 43</li>\n"
"\t</ul>\n"
"\t</li>\n"
"\t<li>Later Prehistoric -4,000 to 43</li>\n"
"\t<li>Prehistoric -1,000 000 to 43</li>\n"
"</ul>\n"
"\n"
"<p><em>Cultural Periods</em></p>\n"
"\n"
"<ul>\n"
"\t<li>Roman 43 to 410 (AD)</li>\n"
"\t<li>Early Medieval 410 to 1066</li>\n"
"\t<li>Medieval 1066 to 1540</li>\n"
"\t<li>Post Medieval 1540 to 1901</li>\n"
"\t<li>Tudor 1485 to 1603</li>\n"
"\t<li>Elizabethan 1558 to 1603</li>\n"
"\t<li>Stuart 1603 to 1714</li>\n"
"\t<li>Jacobean 1603 to 1625</li>\n"
"\t<li>Hanoverian 1714 to 1837</li>\n"
"\t<li>Georgian 1714 to 1830</li>\n"
"\t<li>Victorian 1837 to 1901</li>\n"
"\t<li>20th Century 1901 to 2000\n"
"\t<ul>\n"
"\t\t<li>Early 20th Century 1901 to 1932</li>\n"
"\t\t<li>Edwardian 1902 to 1910</li>\n"
"\t\t<li>First World War 1914 to 1918</li>\n"
"\t\t<li>Mid 20th Century 1933 to 1966</li>\n"
"\t\t<li>Second World War 1939 to 1945</li>\n"
"\t\t<li>Cold War 1946 to 1991</li>\n"
"\t\t<li>Late 20th Century 1967 to 2000</li>\n"
"\t</ul>\n"
"\t</li>\n"
"\t<li>21st Century 2001 to 2100</li>\n"
"\t<li>Uncertain</li>\n"
"</ul>"
msgstr ""

#: cards:1
msgid ""
"<p><strong>Date of Birth</strong></p><p>Where known give the full date of "
"birth</p><p><strong>Birthplace</strong></p><p>Use to record the place where "
"the person was, or is believed to have been, "
"born.</p><p><strong>Mother</strong></p><p>Use to record the name of the "
"biological mother. For step or adoptive parent relationships see HER "
"Parentage.</p><p><strong>Father</strong></p><p>Use to record the name of the"
" biological father. For step or adoptive parent relaitonship see HER "
"Parentage.</p>"
msgstr ""

#: cards:1
msgid ""
"<p><strong>Full Address</strong></p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>Where it is convenient, this can be used to record the full address. This can be used to aid migration from legacy systems with less sophisticated recording practice</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p><strong>Address Parts</strong></p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>To better represent the complexity of addresses each constituent part has been modelled.</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p><strong>Building Name</strong></p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>Use to record the actual name of a building where known.</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p><strong>Building Number</strong></p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>Use to record the number(s) assigned to a building. This may be a single number (eg. 45) or a range separated by a &#39;-&#39;&nbsp;(eg. 13-21).</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p><strong>Building Number Sub-Street</strong></p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>&nbsp;</p>"
msgstr ""

#: cards:1
msgid ""
"<p>This is for recording the current status of an Activity Resource Record.&nbsp; There are three levels:</p>\n"
"\n"
"<ul>\n"
"\t<li><strong>Backlog-Skeleton.</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;Only basic information about the activity has been created, and no associated heritage Records, if applicable, have been created.</li>\n"
"\t<li><strong>Backlog - Full/Published.</strong>&nbsp; All Mandatory and Required data fields have been added, but no associated heritage Records, if applicable, have been created or linked.</li>\n"
"\t<li><strong>Active- Full/Published.&nbsp;</strong>All Mandatory and Required data fields have been added, and all&nbsp;associated heritage Records, if applicable, have been created and linked.&nbsp;</li>\n"
"</ul>"
msgstr ""

